const description = `Restaurant charbroiler burner won't light? LA same-day. Vulcan, Imperial, Garland, MagiKitch'n. $120 commercial.`;

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "One burner on our 6-burner Vulcan VCCB-36 won't light. Others work. What's the cause?",
    a: "Single-burner-out on a multi-burner charbroiler is one of three things in our experience. (1) Carbon and grease buildup at that specific burner port, blocking gas flow at the orifice. Most common single cause on year 2+ restaurant duty. Diagnostic includes burner head removal and deep cleaning, $120 to $200 service if no parts. (2) Spark electrode at that burner failed (electronic ignition models like Vulcan VCCB) or pilot at that station weak (standing pilot models). $260 to $440 spark module replacement, $220 to $340 thermocouple. (3) Gas valve at that station stuck closed. Less common but more expensive, $480 to $680. We test cheap-first."
  },
  {
    q: "Whole charbroiler dead, no burners light. Different diagnostic?",
    a: "Yes. Whole-unit failure points to upstream: gas supply, main gas valve, master pilot or master ignition module. Walk-around test sequence: (1) gas supply isolation valve fully open, (2) gas pressure at unit inlet under load (manometer test, target 6-8 inches WC for natural gas commercial, 11 inches WC for propane), (3) main gas valve solenoid test, (4) master ignition module on electronic units. About 25 to 30 percent of whole-unit failures resolve at the gas pressure measurement (regulator-side problem upstream of the appliance). Repair quote depends on which step fails."
  },
  {
    q: "Burner port carbon buildup on a 3-year-old MagiKitch'n. Routine?",
    a: "Routine on year 2+ restaurant duty. Charbroiler burner ports clog with grease vapor condensate plus carbon from continuous flame contact. Symptom: progressively weaker flame, burner won't light at all when buildup exceeds critical threshold. Cleaning involves burner head removal, port-by-port wire-brush plus compressed air, sometimes acid-based descaling on heavy buildup. Service runs $120 to $260 per burner section depending on buildup severity. Most LA restaurants doing 8 to 14 hr daily service should schedule deep burner cleaning every 6 to 9 months. We see units that haven't been cleaned in 3+ years where the cleaning labor exceeds new-burner-head cost ($340 to $480 per head)."
  },
  {
    q: "Health Department flagged us on burner cleanliness. What do we need?",
    a: "LA County Department of Public Health and equivalent OC, Ventura, San Bernardino, Riverside agencies inspect commercial cooking equipment for grease buildup, surface sanitization, and proper gas combustion (yellow flame indicates incomplete combustion, which produces carbon monoxide). A flagged inspection report typically requires documented professional cleaning service plus follow-up inspection. We document our service work in writing for the customer's HD compliance file: scope of cleaning, before/after photos when requested, parts replaced, gas pressure verification, combustion-quality verification. Standard practice for LA restaurant work."
  },
  {
    q: "Gas pressure drop mid-service. Real concern on commercial charbroilers?",
    a: "Real and not uncommon. A 6-burner commercial charbroiler at full demand pulls 180,000 to 240,000 BTU per hour. If the upstream regulator was sized for the original install but a new fryer or steamer was added later sharing the same supply line, the manifold can run below spec under peak demand. Symptom: burners light fine at startup, run weak or extinguish under full kitchen load. Diagnostic is manometer at unit inlet during peak operation. Fix is typically regulator-side (plumber referral, $200 to $600 depending on scope) rather than appliance-side. We test on every charbroiler call where the operator describes time-of-day inconsistency."
  },
  {
    q: "What's the brand failure-pattern map for LA?",
    a: "Vulcan VCCB (ITW Food Equipment Group): spark module year 5-7, port carbon year 2-4 typical. Imperial IRB (Korean independent): pilot light cluster issue, year 4-6 thermocouple replacement. Garland MGM Master (Welbilt): gas valve year 7-9, premium-tier longevity. MagiKitch'n MK (Middleby, Wolf Industrial commercial line, separate from Wolf residential): radiant tile damage year 5-8 plus burner port carbon. Bakers Pride XX (Middleby): pilot orifice clog year 3-5. Star Ultra-Max (Middleby): mid-tier, spark module year 4-6. Wolf VRB (ITW, again separate from Wolf residential and Wolf Outdoor): premium duty cycle, burner head erosion year 6-8."
  },
  {
    q: "What's your warranty?",
    a: "90 days SDAR labor and parts on every repair. Brand component warranties (Vulcan ITW, Imperial, Garland Welbilt, MagiKitch'n Middleby, Wolf Range ITW, Bakers Pride Middleby, Star Middleby) processed separately through manufacturer authorized service network. BHGS #A49573, BBB A+ accredited, EPA 608 Universal certified #1346255700410."
  }
];

