<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Burner ignition diagnostic</p>
    <h2>About 35 to 40 percent of "won't light" calls resolve at $120 plus burner port cleaning, no parts.</h2>

    <p>Charbroiler burner-ignition failures cluster around five mechanisms. (1) Burner port carbon and grease buildup blocking gas flow at the orifice, year 2+ restaurant duty, $120 to $260 cleaning service per burner section. (2) Spark electrode or spark module failure on electronic ignition models (Vulcan VCCB, newer MagiKitch'n, electronic Wolf VRB), year 5 to 7, $260 to $440 replacement. (3) Pilot light or thermocouple failure on standing-pilot models (Imperial IRB, older MagiKitch'n, older Garland), year 4 to 7, $220 to $340. (4) Gas valve safety lockout (electronic models) or gas valve mechanical failure (older units), $120 reset to $680 replacement. (5) Gas pressure drop at the unit inlet under peak kitchen demand, $200 to $600 regulator-side fix.</p>

    <p>This page covers commercial charbroilers (standalone radiant gas, lava rock, ceramic briquette, and char-rock units). For restaurant range with integrated charbroiler module see <a href="/commercial/range-repair/">range repair</a>. For grill (commercial outdoor cooking grill) see <a href="/commercial/grill-repair/">commercial grill repair</a>. Yes, the categories are confusing in this trade.</p>

    <p>$120 commercial diagnostic, waived with repair. <strong>BHGS #A49573</strong>. <strong>EPA 608 Universal certified #1346255700410</strong>. BBB A+. Phones answered 24/7. Parent: <a href="/commercial/charbroiler-repair/">commercial charbroiler repair</a>.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Field observations</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Top causes by frequency.</h2>
    <ol class="num-list">
      <li><strong>Burner port carbon and grease buildup (year 2+ restaurant duty).</strong> Single most common cause. Continuous grease vapor condensate plus carbon from flame contact. $120-260 cleaning service per burner section, often resolves without parts.</li>
      <li><strong>Spark module / spark electrode failure (electronic ignition, year 5-7).</strong> Click but no spark, or spark but no flame. Vulcan VCCB, electronic MagiKitch'n, electronic Wolf VRB. $260-440 replacement.</li>
      <li><strong>Pilot light / thermocouple failure (standing pilot, year 4-7).</strong> Pilot won't stay lit, won't ignite main burner. Imperial IRB, older MagiKitch'n, older Garland. $220-340.</li>
      <li><strong>Gas valve safety lockout.</strong> Electronic state after 3 failed ignition attempts. $120 reset only or parts as needed.</li>
      <li><strong>Gas valve mechanical failure (year 7+).</strong> Sticking, internal leak, modulation failure. $480-680 replacement.</li>
      <li><strong>Gas supply pressure drop (manifold-shared multi-equipment kitchens).</strong> Below-spec at unit inlet under peak load. Plumber referral $200-600.</li>
      <li><strong>Pilot orifice clog (covered patios, dust).</strong> Less common indoors but happens on patio-installed charbroilers. $120-200 cleaning.</li>
      <li><strong>Burner head erosion (year 8+ heavy duty).</strong> Replacement $340-480 per head.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Diagnostic walkthrough</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Practitioner sequence on every won't-light call.</h2>
    <ol class="num-list">
      <li><strong>Identify the failure scope.</strong> Single burner out vs whole unit. Single-burner points to that station; whole-unit points to upstream supply or master ignition.</li>
      <li><strong>Verify gas supply.</strong> Isolation valve open, supply line uncompromised, no recent kitchen plumbing work that might have closed an upstream valve.</li>
      <li><strong>Manometer pressure under load.</strong> Inlet pressure with the failing burner attempting to fire plus other kitchen equipment running at peak demand. Below-spec triggers regulator-side investigation.</li>
      <li><strong>Visual burner head and port inspection.</strong> Carbon buildup at orifices, heat-warped port plate, visible cracks. Photo documentation.</li>
      <li><strong>Spark or pilot test.</strong> Visual spark at electrode (electronic), audible click on ignition module. Pilot flame strength and steadiness on standing-pilot models.</li>
      <li><strong>Multimeter thermocouple under flame (standing pilot models).</strong> Voltage output during pilot; weak signal indicates failure.</li>
      <li><strong>Gas valve sequence test.</strong> Continuity, solenoid actuation on electronic models; mechanical actuation test on standing-pilot models.</li>
      <li><strong>Combustion quality verification.</strong> Blue flame steady at full firing; yellow or lazy flame indicates incomplete combustion (port issue or pressure issue).</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Honest opinion</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Burner port cleaning is overdue maintenance, not a repair surprise.</h2>
    <p>About a third of LA restaurant charbroiler "won't light" calls resolve at burner port cleaning with no parts replacement. The reason: most operators don't schedule deep burner cleaning until something fails. The internet will tell you to budget for major repair on a 5-year unit; in our experience, a 5-year unit that's been deep-cleaned every 6 to 9 months runs as well as a 1-year unit. Schedule the cleaning, save the surprise. Some shops won't tell you this because cleaning service is lower margin than parts replacement. We tell you because it's what we'd do for our own restaurant.</p>
  </div>
</section>

